Sydney Morning Herald newspapers for 1899 are available for viewing on microfilm at the State Library of New South Wales, amongst other places.

I've checked the SMH for the period from Thursday November 2, 1899 to Saturday November 11, 1899.

During this period, coverage of &quot;The Transvaal War&quot; as it was described usually began on pages ranging from page 3 to page 9.

Amongst none of the sub-headlines on those days are the words &quot;Siege of Ladysmith&quot; used, however there are several sub-headlines during those days referring to Ladysmith.

The Melbourne Cup was held on Tuesday November 7, 1899 and in the Sydney Morning Herald of the next day Wednesday November 8, 1899 on page 7 there is the headline &quot;THE TRANSVAAL WAR&quot; and below it the sub-headline &quot;FIGHTING NEAR LADYSMITH&quot;
On page 10 of that same issue there is the headline 'VICTORIAN RACING CLUB SPRING MEETING  - SECOND (MELBOURNE CUP) DAY - MERRIWEE WINS THE CUP&quot;
It then gives the dateline &quot;Melbourne TUESDAY&quot;

The only other reference to the Melbourn Cup I read during the relevant period was an advertisement by the Sydney Morning Herald advising readers visiting Melbourne for Melbourne Cup that they could have the Sydney Morning Herald posted to them at any address in Victoria for 9d.

The cover price of the Herald at the time was one penny.

Beachcomberaustralia - you may well have been correct that this photograph was taken on Wednesday 8 November, 1899.
